"Duck typing" is a programming concept in which a variable can be used if it "quacks like a duck", regardless of its actual type. In TypeScript, duck typing can be implemented through the use of interfaces. An interface defines a set of properties and methods that an object must have in order to be considered of that type. If an object has all the required properties and methods, it can be used as if it were of the specified type, even if it doesn't explicitly inherit from that type.

Here's an example of duck typing in TypeScript:

```typescript
interface Bird {
  fly(): void;
  quack(): void;
}

function makeBird(bird: Bird) {
  bird.fly();
  bird.quack();
}

// This object implements the Bird interface through duck typing
const donaldDuck: Bird = {
  fly() {
    console.log("Flying like a duck!");
  },
  quack() {
    console.log("Quack!");
  },
};

makeBird(donaldDuck);
```

In this example, the `donaldDuck` object implements the `Bird` interface by having all the required properties and methods. Even though it doesn't explicitly inherit from the `Bird` interface, it can still be used as if it were a `Bird`, since it "quacks like a duck".

